[[Image:Boat by Hamid Naderi Yeganeh.jpg|thumb|upright=1|An example of ''Boat''<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ams.org/mathimagery/displayimage.php?album=40&pid=617#top_display_media|title="Boat," by Hamid Naderi Yeganeh|publisher=[[American Mathematical Society]] |date=September 16, 2015 |accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref>]] '''Boat''' is a set of boat-like works of [[Mathematics and art|mathematical art]] introduced by mathematical artist [[Hamid Naderi Yeganeh]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ams.org/mathimagery/thumbnails.php?album=40|title=Mathematical Concepts Illustrated by Hamid Naderi Yeganeh|publisher=[[American Mathematical Society]] |date=November 2014 |accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Catch of the day: mathematician nets weird, complex fish |url= https://www.theguardian.com/science/alexs-adventures-in-numberland/2015/feb/24/catch-of-the-day-mathematician-nets-weird-complex-fish |date= February 24, 2015 |first=Alex |last=Bellos |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>
The work is defined by [[trigonometric functions]]. One instance is composed of 2000 [[line segments]] where for each <math>k=1, 2, 3, \ldots , 2000</math> the endpoints of the k-th line segment are: :<math> \left(\cos\left(\frac{6\pi k}{2000}\right)-i\cos\left(\frac{12\pi k}{2000}\right)\right)e^{\frac{3\pi i}{4}} </math> and :<math> \left(\sin\left(\frac{4\pi k}{2000}+\frac{\pi}{8}\right)+i\sin\left(\frac{2\pi k}{2000}+\frac{\pi}{3}\right)\right)e^{\frac{3\pi i}{4}} </math>.<ref>{{cite news |title=Importing Things From the Real World Into the Territory of Mathematics! |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/hamid-naderi-yeganeh/importing-things-from-the_b_8111912.html |date=September 11, 2015 |first=Hamid |last=Naderi Yeganeh |work=[[Huffington Post]] (blog)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mathematically Precise Crosshatching |url= http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/symbiartic/mathematically-precise-crosshatching/ |date=August 6, 2015 |first=Glendon |last=Mellow |work=[[Scientific American]] (blog)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=When Math Transforms into Art |url= http://thescienceexplorer.com/technology/when-math-transforms-art |date=February 3, 2016 |first=Elizabeth |last=Knowles |work=The Science Explorer}}</ref>
